  <d:title>Ratio</d:title>
  <d:para>
    In his book <d:emphasis role="italic">Elements of Algebra</d:emphasis>,
    Euler says that anything we can increase or decrase is <d:emphasis
    role="italic">magnitude</d:emphasis> or <d:emphasis
    role="italic">quantity</d:emphasis>.
  </d:para>
  <d:para>
    We will study ratios of quantities in this chapter. Many of you might
    already be knowing about ratios from earlier classes. A ratio is nothing
    but a comparison between two quantities of same kine. For example, 4 balls
    vs 7 balls or 12 shoes vs 8 shoes.
  </d:para>
  <d:para>
    A ratio beween two qualtities Q1 and Q2 is written as Q1:Q2 most of the
    time. Q1 or the first term is called the <d:emphasis
    role="bold">antecedent</d:emphasis> and the Q2 or the second term is called
    the <d:emphasis role="bold">consequent</d:emphasis>.
  </d:para>
  <d:para>
    To measure the ratio between two quantities typically we use fractions. A
    reduced fraction is tells us about one quanity being multiples of another
    or part of that. For example, 2 dozen bananas compared to 6 bananas can be
    written as <math
    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#x2217;</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow><mn>6</mn></mfrac></math>
    or 4.
  </d:para>
  <d:para>
    Ratios are <d:emphasis role="italic">abstract quantities</d:emphasis>
    because they are sheer numbers. In practice, considering our previous
    example we can say 2 dozen banans are four times 6 bananas. This four is an
    abstract quantity because it does not have a physical form.
  </d:para>
  <d:para>
    Clearly, you can see that
    <math
        xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mrow><mi>Q</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>Q</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>Q</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>Q</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>
    so the ratio does not change if numerator or antecedent and denominator or
    consequent are multiplied by the same quantity.
  </d:para>
  <d:sect1>
    <d:title>Comparing Two Ratios</d:title>
    <d:para>
      To compare two ratios we need to make their denominator same the we can
      deduce if they are equal or unequal. For example consider two ratios
      r1:r2 and r3:r4. Then, we can have
      <d:informalequation>
        <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mtable columnspacing="0em" rowspacing="3pt" columnalign="right left"><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn><mi>r</mi><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mtext>&#xA0;</mtext><mtext>&#xA0;</mtext><mi mathvariant="normal">&amp;</mi><mtext>&#xA0;</mtext><mtext>&#xA0;</mtext><mfrac><mrow><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></math>
        </d:informalequation>
        Now since consequent is same for both the ratios we can determine which
        ratio is bigger or equal or smaller by determining if r1r4 is bigger or
        equal or smaller as compared to r2r3.
    </d:para>
  </d:sect1>
  <d:sect1>
    <d:title>Ratio of Ratios</d:title>
    <d:para>
      Clearly, a ratio can be represented by a fraction of two integers. Now
      let us try to see what happens to ratio of two ratios.Consider two
      ratios: a:b and math:c:d. Thus we can write ratio of these two raios as
      fraction
      <d:informalequation>
        <math
            xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mfrac><mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>d</mi></mfrac></mfrac><mtext>&#xA0;</mtext><mtext>&#xA0;</mtext><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi><mtext>&#xA0;</mtext><mtext>&#xA0;</mtext><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>
      </d:informalequation>
      Therefore, we can conclude that it is eqauivalent to ad:bc.
    </d:para>
    <d:para>
      When I said a ratio can be applied as a fraction of two integers then
      that applied to finite numbers. A surd like <math
      xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt></math>
      is not a finite number because certain portion of its fractional part is
      not recurring. Therefore, when a surd if involved in a ratio cannot be
      represented as a fraction of two integers.
    </d:para>
    <d:para>
      If we can represent a ratio exactly by two integers the quantities are
      called <d:emphasis role="bold">commensurable</d:emphasis> else they are
      called <d:emphasis role="bold">incommensurable</d:emphasis>.
    </d:para>
  </d:sect1>
  <d:sect1>
    <d:title>Compounding Ratios</d:title>
    <d:para>
      Ratios are compounded by multiplying ratios. The multiplication is done
      in simple fashion. Antecedents with antecedents and consequents with
      consequents.
    </d:para>
    <d:para>
      For example, consider some ratios: a:b, c:d and e:f. The compounded ratio
      is abc:def.
    </d:para>
  </d:sect1>
  <d:sect1>
    <d:title>Duplicate Ratios</d:title>
    <d:para>
      When a ratio is compounded with itself once it is called <d:emphasis
      role="bold">duplicate ratio</d:emphasis>. If it is compounded twice,
      it is called <d:emphasis role="bold">triplicate ratio</d:emphasis>. If a
      square root is taken, it is called <d:emphasis
      role="bold">subduplicate ratio</d:emphasis>.
    </d:para>
  </d:sect1>
  <d:sect1>
    <d:title>Antecedent vs Consequent</d:title>
    <d:para>
      A ratio is of <d:emphasis role="italic">greater inequality</d:emphasis>,
      or <d:emphasis role="italic">less inequality</d:emphasis> or <d:emphasis
      role="italic">of equality</d:emphasis> depending on whether antecedent is
      greater or smaller or equal to the consequent.
    </d:para>
  </d:sect1>
  <d:sect1>
    <d:title>Common Properties of Ratios</d:title>
    <d:para>
      A ratio of greater inequality is diminished and a ratio of less
      inequality is increased if we add same quantity to both of its terms. What
      is meant is no matter the ratio if you add a quantity to that then it
      will approach towards one if originally it is positive. You should be
      able to draw similar behavior for negative ratios and for subtraction as
      well. Say, we subtract a quantity from both of its terms then the
      ratio will move away from 1 on the number axis. Let us see how it works.
    </d:para>
    <d:para>
      Let us consider a negative ratio. In that case, if we add a positive
      number to both its terms then ratio will move towards from -1 and if we
      subtract then it will move away from from -1.
    </d:para>
    <d:para>
      Let <math
      xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mfrac></math>
      be a ratio and we add x to both its terms so we have <math
      xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>
      as our new ratio. Now,
    </d:para>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mfrac><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:para>
      and aâˆ’b is positive or negative depending upon the fact whether a is
      greater or smaller than b. Hence, if
    </d:para>
    <d:inlineequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>a</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mfrac><mo>&gt;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>
    </d:inlineequation>
    <d:para>and if</d:para>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>a</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mfrac><mo>&lt;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:para>
      Similarly, it can be proved that a ratio of greater inequality is
      icreased and a ratio of less inequality is decreased if we subtract same
      quanitty to both its terms. When two or more ratios are equal, we can
      denote that by a single symbol, which helps us in many ways. Let,
    </d:para>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>d</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>e</mi><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>,</mo></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:para>and</d:para>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>r</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><msup><mi>d</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>r</mi><msup><mi>f</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></msup></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:para>Let,</d:para>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>d</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>e</mi><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>;</mo></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:para>then,</d:para>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>d</mi><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>;</mo></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:para>Hence,</d:para>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><msup><mi>k</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mi>q</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>q</mi><msup><mi>d</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><msup><mi>k</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mi>r</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>r</mi><msup><mi>f</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><msup><mi>k</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>;</mo></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>&#x21D2;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>r</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><msup><mi>d</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>r</mi><msup><mi>f</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><msup><mi>k</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><msup><mi>d</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><msup><mi>k</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>r</mi><msup><mi>f</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><msup><mi>k</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><msup><mi>d</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>r</mi><msup><mi>f</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mi>n</mi></msup></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>&#x21D2;</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>r</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><msup><mi>d</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>r</mi><msup><mi>f</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:para>
      Similarly, we can say that when a a number of fractions are equal, each
      of them is equal to the sum of all the numerators divided by the sum of
      denominators,
    </d:para>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>&#x21D2;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>e</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>d</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>b</mi><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>d</mi><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>f</mi><mi>k</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>d</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>.</mo></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:para>
      If, <math
      xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>,</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mfrac></math>
      be unequal fractions, of which denominators are all having the same sign,
      then the fraction
      <d:informalequation>
        <math
            xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>
      </d:informalequation>
      lies in magnitude between the greatest and least of them.
    </d:para>
    <d:para>
      Let all the denominators are positive. Let, <math
      xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>r</mi></msub></mfrac></math>
      be the least fraction, and denote it by k; then
      <d:informalequation>
        <math
            xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>r</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>;</mo><mo>&#x2234;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><mo>;</mo></math>
      </d:informalequation>
      <d:informalequation>
        <math
            xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>1</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>1</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>;</mo><mo>&#x2234;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>1</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>1</mi></msub><mo>;</mo></math>
      </d:informalequation>
      <d:informalequation>
        <math
            xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>2</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>2</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>;</mo><mo>&#x2234;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>2</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>2</mi></msub><mo>;</mo></math>
      </d:informalequation>
      and so on.
      <d:inlineequation><math
                            xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>&#x2234;</mo></math></d:inlineequation>
      by addition,
    </d:para>
    <d:para>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>&#x2234;</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>;</mo><mtext>that
      is,</mtext><mo>&gt;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>r</mi></msub></mfrac></math>
      Similarly, we may prove that
      <d:informalequation>
        <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>;</mo><mtext>that is,</mtext><mo>&lt;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>s</mi></msub></mfrac></math>
      </d:informalequation>
      where, <math
      xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mi>s</mi></msub></mfrac></math>
      is greatest of the given ratios.
    </d:para>
    <d:para>
      If we have two equations containing three unknown variables in the first
      degree such as
    </d:para>
    <d:equation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>y</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>
    </d:equation>
    <d:equation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>y</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>
    </d:equation>
    <d:para>
      Rewriting these we can have following;
    </d:para>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mfenced><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>z</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mfenced><mfrac><mi>y</mi><mi>z</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:informalequation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>z</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mfrac><mi>y</mi><mi>z</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo></math>
    </d:informalequation>
    <d:para>Solving these we obtain,</d:para>
    <d:equation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>z</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mfrac><mi>y</mi><mi>z</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>
    </d:equation>
    <d:para>
      So we can see that for x coefficients of y and z are used and for y, that
      of x and z are used and so on in a cyclic manner as given in image below:
    </d:para>
    <d:figure>
      <d:mediaobject>
        <d:imageobject>
          <d:imagedata fileref="../images/ratio_cycle.png" align="center" />
        </d:imageobject>
      </d:mediaobject>
      <d:title>Cross-multiplication of coefficients</d:title>
    </d:figure>
    <d:para>
      Multiply the coefficients as indicated by the arrows. The ascending
      arrows are positive and descending ones are negative. This is called the
      <d:emphasis role="bold">Rule of Cross Multiplication</d:emphasis>.
    </d:para>
    <d:para>
      Now expanding on previous discussion consider following set of three
      equations which includes 2.1 and 2.2 given earlier:
    </d:para>
    <d:equation>
      <math
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>b</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>y</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>
    </d:equation>
    
  </d:sect1>
</d:chapter>
